in Huambo, Angola (Photo by Tim Graham/Getty)\nPrince Harry is set to continue his late mother’s anti-landmine work.\nTo champion Diana, Princess of Wales’s cause, HRH will support a bid to rid the world of the dangerous explosives by 2025.\nOdeon cinema collapses into city centre street\nHarry is expected to give a keynote speech at a Kensington Palace reception to mark International Mine Awareness Day.\nThe Prince is expected to pay tribute to his late mother’s work at the Landmine Free World 2025 event – ahead of the 20th anniversary of the Princess’s death this year.\nJust months before she died in a car crash in 1997, Diana, photographed wearing a protective visor and vest, walked through a mine field in Angola being cleared by the HALO Trust.\nPrince Harry visiting the HALO Trust in Tete Province, Mozambique, Africa back in 2010 (Picture: Rex)\nShe spoke out vociferously against the sale and use of landmines, and controversially called for an international ban on the Trust’s 25th Anniversary Appeal, has followed in his mother’s footsteps by visiting mine fields in Angola and Mozambique.\nA Kensington Palace spokesman said: ‘In the year marking the 20th anniversary 128 countries signed the Ottawa Treaty to ban the use and production of anti-personnel mines.\nMany of those involved in the 1997 campaign will attend the reception, along with senior representatives of governments who support international mine action.
